T1  - ECONOMIES WITH PUBLIC PROJECTS: EFFICIENCY AND DECENTRALIZATION*
AU  - Graziano, Maria Gabriella
Y1  - 2007/08/01
PY  - 2007
DA  - 2007/08/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-2354.2007.00453.x
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
SP  - 1037
EP  - 1063
VL  - 48
IS  - 3
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-2354.2007.00453.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - The article deals with the two fundamental theorems of welfare economics for production economies with a finite set of agents, infinitely many private goods, and a set of public projects. The problem of efficiency and decentralization is addressed under the following very general assumptions: (a) the commodity?price duality is endowed with a consistent locally convex topology; (b) the set of public projects is without any mathematical structure. Moreover, any agent is characterized by a nonordered preference relation depending on consumption goods and public projects. Approximate and exact welfare theorems are discussed throughout the article.
ER  - 

